  "prompt": "What are the comparative legal approaches to money laundering across different nations?",
  "response": "There are significant variations in money laundering legal approaches across different nations, though most share some common core principles:\n\n1. United States Approach\n- Comprehensive Bank Secrecy Act\n- Strict reporting requirements\n- Aggressive prosecution\n- Significant financial penalties\n- Focus on international cooperation\n\n2. European Union Approach\n- Unified Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Harmonized regulatory framework\n- Strong emphasis on financial institution compliance\n- Enhanced customer due diligence requirements\n- Centralized information sharing mechanisms\n\n3. United Kingdom Model\n- Proceeds of Crime Act\n- Sophisticated risk-based regulatory system\n- Emphasis on financial intelligence\n- Strong cross-agency collaboration\n- Advanced technological monitoring\n\n4. Swiss Approach\n- Traditionally more banking secrecy-oriented\n- Increasing international transparency\n- Complex multi-layer compliance mechanisms\n- Gradual alignment with international standards\n\n5. Developing Nations' Approaches\n- Often less sophisticated regulatory frameworks\n- Varying levels of implementation\n- Limited technological monitoring capabilities\n- Higher vulnerability to systemic corruption\n\nCommon Elements:\n- Customer identification requirements\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- International information exchanges\n- Criminal asset seizure provisions\n\nEach jurisdiction reflects unique legal, cultural, and economic contexts.",
